commit_description:
, fixing the remaining bug and ensuring that consecutive non-spread properties don't get turned into separate objects:

```js
// before
var obj = { ...a, b: b, c: c } --> var obj = Object.assign( {}, a, {b: b}, {c: c})

// after
var obj = { ...a, b: b, c: c } --> var obj = Object.assign( {}, a, {b: b, c: c})
```

See merge request

, and adds support for intelligent destructuring in variable declarations:

```js
// input
var { foo, bar } = obj;
console.log( foo );
console.log( bar );
console.log( bar );

// old output
var foo = obj.foo;
var bar = obj.bar;
console.log( foo );
console.log( bar );
console.log( bar );

// new output
var bar = obj.bar;
console.log( obj.foo );
console.log( bar );
console.log( bar );
```

(This can create non-negligible savings, even post-minification.)

See merge request
